text.tspan: As opposed to active coping, avoidant coping is characterized by activities that aid in the
denial of the problem and ignore the issue at hand ("UCLA Dual Diagnosis," n.d.). Students are
observed to engage in various distractions and self-soothing practices such as yoga, meditation,
deep breathing, praying, private self-expressions (e.g., through diary entries and crying),
sleeping, and eating to provide immediate relief from negative preoccupying thoughts (Parikh et
al., 2015). In the same study, some students participated in activities like spending time with
friends, studying, and playing with children, while others took steps to avoid confrontations with
parents and teachers in times of academic difficulties. Substance use involving cigarettes,
tobacco, alcohol, and cannabis was also reported in various studies to reduce stress and tension
(Mathew et al., 2015; Parikh et al., 2015; Shaikh et al., 2018). However, such methods were
reported to harm the students further and increase anxiety.
Suicide has been seen as the last resort for severe stressors like sexual assault and rape,
and severe and sustained academic pressure (Parikh et al., 2015). In the past, there have been
many incidents where students have committed suicide during examination days (Bhargava &
Tiwari, 2019). Sharma et al. (2015) found that almost 16% of adolescents had suicidal ideation,
and 5% attempted suicide. These alarming statistics were reproduced by Arun & Chavan (2009),
in which 8.82% of the sample of 6th through 12th-grade students in Chandigarh reported life as a
burden, 6% expressed suicidal thoughts, and 0.39% reported suicidal attempts.
